The '''orange-billed lorikeet''' ('''''Neopsittacus pullicauda''''') is a [[species]] in the Old World parrot [[Family (taxonomy)|family]] [[Psittaculidae]]. First [[Species description|described]] by the German [[ornithologist]] [[Ernst Hartert]] in 1896, it is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[New Guinea]], where it mainly inhabits [[Mossy forest|cloud forest]], [[Woodland edge|forest edges]], and cleared areas bordering forests at elevations of {{Convert|2,100–3,800|m|ft|abbr=on}}. Adults are {{Convert|18|cm|in|abbr=on}} long on average and weigh {{Convert|25-40|g|oz|abbr=on}}, and are mainly green in color, with a red underside and narrow yellow streaking on the cheeks. It looks similar to the closely related [[yellow-billed lorikeet]], but is smaller in size, has more richly coloured [[plumage]], and has a smaller, orange bill. 

The species feeds on pollen, nectar, flowers, fruits, and, uncommonly, seeds. They sometimes forage together with yellow-billed lorikeets at fruiting trees, but are rarely found with species of other [[genera]]. Breeding takes place in October; nests are made in holes in tall trees and contain two eggs. It is listed as being of [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] due to its large range and lack of severe declines in its population.

== Taxonomy and systematics ==
The orange-billed lorikeet was [[Species description|formally described]] as a [[species]] by the German [[ornithologist]] [[Ernst Hartert]] in 1896 based on specimens from the "Victoria district" in the [[Owen Stanley Range]] in [[New Guinea]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Hartert |first=Ernst |date=1896 |title=List of three small collections from British New Guinea, mostly brought together in the Owen Stanley Range |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/22554#page/35/mode/1up |journal=[[Novitates Zoologicae]] |volume=3 |pages=8–19 [17] }}</ref> The generic name ''Neopsittacus'' is from the [[Greek language|Greek]] νεος (''neos''), meaning new, and ψιττακος (''psittakos''), meaning parrot. The [[specific epithet]] ''pullicauda'' is from the [[Latin]] ''pullus'', meaning dark-colored, and ''cauda'', meaning tail.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jobling|first=James A.|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names|publisher=[[Christopher Helm]]|year=2010|isbn=978-1-4081-3326-2|pages=268, 324}}</ref> Alternative [[common name]]s for the species include emerald lorikeet, alpine lorikeet and orange-billed mountain lorikeet.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|last1=Beehler|first1=Bruce|title=Birds of New Guinea: Distribution, Taxonomy, and Systematics|last2=Pratt|first2=Thane|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|year=2016|isbn=978-0-691-16424-3|location=|page=250}}</ref><ref name=":3" />

The species shows [[Cline (biology)|clinal]] variation (gradual variation in its appearance along its range), with birds from western populations being smaller and paler than birds from southeastern ones.<ref name=":1" /> It is treated as [[Monotypic taxon|having one subspecies]] by the [[International Ornithologists' Union]];<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-07-15 |editor-last=Gill |editor-first=Frank |editor2-last=Donsker |editor2-first=David |editor3-last=Rasmussen |editor3-first=Pamela |editor3-link=Pamela C. Rasmussen |title=Parrots, cockatoos |url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/new/bow/parrots/ |access-date=2023-09-08 |website=IOC World Bird List |language=en-US}}</ref> however, some authorities recognize as many as three subspecies on the basis of differences in appearance, with populations from central western [[New Guinea]] separated as ''N. p. alpinus''{{Efn|Said to have an orange breast, compared to the nominate subspecies's red one, and a darker red belly.<ref name="BOW" />}} and populations from northeastern New Guinea separated as ''N. p. socialis''.''{{Efn|Said to be darker overall than the nominate subspecies.<ref name="BOW" />}}''<ref name="BOW">{{Citation |last1=Collar |first1=Nigel |title=Orange-billed Lorikeet (''Neopsittacus pullicauda'') |date=2020-03-04 |url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/orblor1/1.0/introduction |work=Birds of the World |editor-last=Billerman |editor-first=Shawn M. |access-date=2023-09-07 |publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology |language=en |doi=10.2173/bow.orblor1.01 |last2=Boesman |first2=Peter F. D. |s2cid=241483025 |editor2-last=Keeney |editor2-first=Brooke K. |editor3-last=Rodewald |editor3-first=Paul G. |editor4-last=Schulenberg |editor4-first=Thomas S. |url-access=subscription}}</ref>

The orange-billed lorikeet is one of two species in the [[genus]] ''[[Neopsittacus]]''. It and the [[yellow-billed lorikeet]] are [[Basal (phylogenetics)|basal]] within a [[clade]] (group of organisms descending from a common ancestor) formed by ''Neopsittacus'', ''[[Lorius]]'', ''[[Psitteuteles]]'', ''[[Parvipsitta]]'', ''[[Pseudeos]]'', ''[[Chalcopsitta]]'', ''[[Glossoptilus]]'', ''[[Glossopsitta]]'', ''[[Saudareos]]'', ''[[Eos (bird)|Eos]]'', and ''[[Trichoglossus]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Joseph |first1=Leo |last2=Merwin |first2=Jon |last3=Smith |first3=Brian Tilston |date=2020-07-02 |title=Improved systematics of lorikeets reflects their evolutionary history and frames conservation priorities |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/01584197.2020.1779596 |journal=Emu |language=en |volume=120 |issue=3 |pages=201–215 |doi=10.1080/01584197.2020.1779596 |bibcode=2020EmuAO.120..201J |s2cid=222094508|url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Brian Tilston |last2=Mauck |first2=William M |last3=Benz |first3=Brett W |last4=Andersen |first4=Michael J |date=2020-07-01 |editor-last=Holland |editor-first=Barbara |title=Uneven missing data skew phylogenomic relationships within the lories and lorikeets |url=https://academic.oup.com/gbe/article/12/7/1131/5848646 |journal=Genome Biology and Evolution |language=en |volume=12 |issue=7 |pages=1131–1147 |doi=10.1093/gbe/evaa113 |pmc=7486955 |pmid=32470111}}</ref>

