== Description ==
The orange-billed lorikeet is a small species of [[Loriini|lorikeet]], with a length of around {{Convert|18|cm|in|abbr=on}} and a weight of {{Convert|25-40|g|oz|abbr=on}}.<ref name="BOW" /> Adults are mainly dark emerald green, with red underparts and narrow yellow streaking on the cheeks.<ref name="BOW" /><ref name=":2">{{Cite book |last1=Pratt |first1=Thane K. |title=Birds of New Guinea |last2=Beehler |first2=Bruce M. |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |year=2015 |isbn=978-0-691-09562-2 |edition=2nd |location=[[Princeton, New Jersey]] |pages=354–355 |language=en}}</ref> The flanks and wings are also emerald green; the underside of the tail is a duller green, with a red patch at the base. The underwing is bright red and is especially prominent in flight.<ref name=":2" /> The [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]] and beak are orange, with a yellow tip to the latter, and the feet are dark grey.<ref name=":3" /> Immatures are duller in color, with less red on their underparts and an orangish-brown bill.<ref name="BOW" /> [[Fledge|Fledglings]] have yellow beaks, which turn orange at around 6 months of age.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Bell |first=H. L. |date=January 1984 |title=New or confirmatory information on some species of New Guinean birds |url=https://afo.birdlife.org.au/afo/index.php/afo/article/view/1109 |journal=[[Australian Bird Watcher]] |volume=10 |issue=7 |pages=219–220}}</ref>

Other than the yellow-billed lorikeet, no other parrot in the species' range has a similar coloration.<ref name=":2" /> Compared with the yellow-billed lorikeet, it is smaller in size, has more richly coloured [[plumage]], and has a smaller, orange bill.<ref name=":3">{{Cite book |last1=Ripley |first1=Sydney Dillon |url=https://elischolar.library.yale.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1018&=&context=peabody_museum_natural_history_bulletin&=&sei-redir=1&referer=https%253A%252F%252Fscholar.google.com%252Fscholar%253Fstart%253D30%2526q%253DNeopsittacus%252Bpullicauda%2526hl%253Den%2526as_sdt%253D0%252C5#search=%22Neopsittacus%20pullicauda%22 |title=A Systematic and Ecological Study of Birds of New Guinea |date=1964 |publisher=[[Peabody Museum of Natural History]] |series=19 |location=[[New Haven, Connecticut]] |pages=32–33 |language=en-US |author-link=Sidney Dillon Ripley}}</ref> Additionally, it can also be distinguished by its flanks and wings being the same shade of green, the underside of the tail being dull green with red at the base, and the lack of an olive tint to the top of its head.<ref name=":2" />

=== Vocalisations ===
The species is very vocal and gives a variety of calls, including a high upslurred "tseet" and other, longer high-pitched calls.<ref name="BOW" /> Although these calls are similar to those of the yellow-billed lorikeet, they tend to be softer, more high-pitched, and more musical.<ref name=":2" />

== Distribution and habitat ==
The orange-billed lorikeet is [[Endemism|endemic]] to the island of New Guinea. It inhabits [[forest canopy]], [[Woodland edge|forest edges]], and cleared areas bordering forests at high elevations in mountains in the [[New Guinea Highlands|Central Range]] and the [[Huon Peninsula]], but is absent from the [[Bird's Head Peninsula]]. It prefers [[Mossy forest|cloud forest]] at elevations of {{Convert|2,100–3,800|m|ft|abbr=on}}, but has been recorded at elevations as low as {{Convert|800|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=":1" /><ref name="BOW" /> [[Vagrancy (biology)|Vagrancy]] at lower elevations suggests that the species may sporadically migrate altitudinally;<ref name="BOW" /> ''Neopsittacus'' is one of only five genera in the order [[Psittaciformes]] to evolve to be nomadic.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Mettke-Hofmann |first1=Claudia |last2=Wink |first2=Michael |last3=Winkler |first3=Hans |last4=Leisler |first4=Bernd |date=2005-01-01 |title=Exploration of environmental changes relates to lifestyle |url=http://academic.oup.com/beheco/article/16/1/247/206619/Exploration-of-environmental-changes-relates-to |journal=Behavioral Ecology |language=en |volume=16 |issue=1 |pages=247–254 |doi=10.1093/beheco/arh159 |quote=Considering residency as the ancestral state for the Order Psittaciformes, nomadism seems to have evolved three times independently in the clades ''Charmosyna'', ''Psephotus''/''Northiella'', and ''Neopsittacus''/''Trichoglossus''...|doi-access=free }}</ref> At lower elevations, it often inhabits the same areas as the yellow-billed lorikeet.<ref name=":1" />

== Behaviour and ecology ==
Orange-billed lorikeets are typically found in small flocks.<ref name=":2" /> They feed on pollen, nectar, flowers, fruits, and, uncommonly, seeds. Plants it is known to feed upon include the [[seed cones]] of ''[[Papuacedrus papuana]]'' and the berries of ''[[Sericolea pullei]]''. It is more [[nectarivorous]] than the yellow-billed lorikeet.<ref name="BOW" /> They sometimes forage together with yellow-billed lorikeets at fruiting trees, but are rarely found with other species.<ref name=":2" /> Its breeding season is in October. It nests in hollows in tall trees, where it lays [[Clutch (eggs)|clutches]] of 2 eggs.<ref name="BOW" /> The orange-billed lorikeet is parasitised by a variety of insects, including the [[Rhinonyssidae|rhinonyssid]] mites ''[[Mesonyssus alisteri]]'' and [[Tinaminyssus trichoglossi|''Tinaminyssus'' ''trichoglossi'']],<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Wilson |first=Nixon |date=1968 |title=New records and a new species of ''Mesonyssus'' (Mesostigmata: Rhinonyssidae) from parrots (Psittaciformes: Psittacidae) |journal=The Journal of Parasitology |volume=54 |issue=2 |page=397 |doi=10.2307/3276960 |jstor=3276960 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Wilson |first=Nixon |date=1964 |title=New records and description of Rhinonyssidae, mostly from New Guinea (Acarina: Mesostigmata) |url=http://hbs.bishopmuseum.org/pi/pdf/6(2)-357.pdf |journal=Pacific Insects |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=374–375}}</ref> the [[Philopteridae|philopterid]] chewing louse ''[[Psittaconirmus zinki]]'',<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Price |first1=Roger D. |last2=Clayton |first2=Dale H. |date=1983 |title=A review of the genus ''Psittaconirmus'' (Mallophaga: Philopteridae) from South Pacific parrots (Psittaciformes) |url=http://hbs.bishopmuseum.org/pi/pdf/25(1)-56.pdf |journal=International Journal of Entomology |volume=25 |issue=1 |pages=56–70 [63]}}</ref> and the [[Menoponidae|menoponid]] chewing louse ''[[Eomenopon semilunare]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Price |first=Roger D. |date=1966 |title=The genus ''Eomenopon'' Harrison with descriptions of seven new species (Mallophaga: Menoponidae) |url=https://phthiraptera.myspecies.info/sites/phthiraptera.info/files/1032.pdf |journal=Pacific Insects |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=17–28 [22]}}</ref>

== Status ==
The species is listed as being of [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] due to its large range and lack of severe declines in its population.<ref name="iucn" /> It is listed on [[Appendix II]] of [[CITES]]. It is common throughout most of its range and is not particularly threatened by habitat loss or the wildlife trade.<ref name="BOW" />

